Do the BIM! This week on the Midnight Mass Podcast, Peaches and Michael discover the power of rock in celebration of 1980's THE APPLE! In addition to discussing the film's amped up musical numbers, our hosts muse over whether Eurovision had a profound impact on this cult classic's vision of the future. Joining the conversation is proud member of the Children of the Popcorn Brian Knecht, whose examination of the world presented in the movie reveals a deeply interwoven global aesthetic. Then, acclaimed filmmaker and podcast host Julia Marchese stops by to talk about her longtime love of THE APPLE's unapologetic vision of a magnificently musical tomorrow. From glam devils to actual vampires, this episode has it all! GO!

A Christmas Gaiety at the Royal Albert Hall.

This was Drag and Queer Herstory being made! @thepeacheschrist was the first drag queen to ever perform at this historic venue of Royal Albert Hall, the most important snd prestigious in the UK - and doing so in a spectacle that unapologetically Queer, that dared to be irreverent and kinky and camp, that gave space and highlighted so many queer artists from different areas of our culture, incorporating them with something as mainstream and established as the BBC Concert Orchestra. I'm in awe of everything this team of artists has brought forward. This was my first time in Royal Albert Hall and it was a spectacular intro and an amazing experience I will remember forever. 

Pictured here @thepeacheschrist, conductor extraordinaire @eoutwater, the BBC Concert Orchestra, drag performers @legateauchocolat @cheddar_gorgeous @pixiepolite, bdsm star @teddy_bryce (more on him as a separate post) and West End superstar @marishawallace. I am shocked and horrified to bring this news to you.  I am living in a real-life nightmare so forgive me if I don’t have all the answers just now. This morning, in London, England I went to collect my dear friend Heklina, who is costarring with me in a Mommie Queerest show here, and found her dead.  I do not know the cause of death yet.  I know this is shocking news and I am beyond stunned, but I wanted to let folks know what has happened.  Heklina is not just my best friend, but a beloved icon of our community.  I am a mess. Given this crisis, please do not try to contact me as I am utterly heartbroken, stunned, and focusing on what needs to get done next.  I shall be in touch.

I will be flying home to San Francisco from London tomorrow, Friday. I have been waiting for some more news about Heklina and the possible release of our possessions before returning. The latest:

“A forensic post mortem was completed by Dr Poole on 06/04/2023 at 1530hrs at Westminster mortuary. Dr Poole’s findings were that there is no obvious sign of an assault and no sign of foul play. Further tests will need to be conducted to help find a cause of death.” 

I’m relieved for a number of reasons. This determination meant our apartment is no longer considered a crime scene and I’m now waiting for an officer to collect me and escort me there so that I can collect our stuff. I am slightly afraid to return but intend to walk through my fear. I look forward to reuniting with Nihat at home tomorrow night. I’m ready to collapse. Thank you for all the love and support. I’ve been receiving it fully while trying to stay focused here.

People have asked me about Heklina's journey home to the U.S. and I want to let you all know how special it was. Much has been said about Heklina's Icelandic roots on her mother's side but you may not know that she was Native American on her father's side. I remember some time ago we were doing a show together in Portland and Heklina was excited to introduce me to a giant group of these incredible family members. They welcomed me with open arms. Heklina had become very close with them, but in particular a queer cousin of hers, Lynzy. I loved meeting Lynzy and her wife that night. It was Lynzy who flew to London and was there for the cremation so that Heklina wasn't alone. As part of their Chippewa culture, Lynzy cut off a VERY long braid that she had been growing for over ten years and placed it with Heklina for the cremation process. Lynzy explained to me that it's a sign of mourning and honor to send with their blood. It's a sign of the life they shared and their new life apart. Lynzy carried Heklina and her belongings back home to California in lieu of relying on a shipping service. I cannot thank her enough for honoring our friend in this way. I had so much stress and anxiety leaving Heklina in England and I'm glad that someone so wonderful was there to bring her home. @hart.throb

Hi everyone; here’s my tribute to the amazing #Heklina. 

I was moved to create this image after visiting the beautiful Pere-Lachaise cemetery in Paris, where Oscar Wilde and Gertrude Stein were laid to rest. The latin at the top translates to “Live My Life”, which is a reference to Heklina’s Drag Time podcast. If you haven’t listened, you should.

Thank you Heklina.

In the last two years, @lgbtasylumproject has been receiving a crucial grant from the SF Mayor’s Office for transgender, gender non-conforming and intersex asylum seekers to get free legal services for their asylum applications and court hearings.

A few days ago, the LGBT Asylum Project received the news that this program is being cut by the Mayor’s Office. 

These services are life-saving services. It’s crucial that we provide these services in San Francisco because deportation means death for these asylum seekers.

We urge you to contact the Mayor’s Office via e-mail or calling their office and tell them not to cut services for TGNCI asylum seekers.

Heklina was included in Entertainment Weekly’s list of celebrities we lost in 2023. As this crazy year comes to a close, there’s this gigantic life-changing event that will forever define 2023 for me. Finding her dead is still a surreal nightmare and what’s really frustrating and upsetting is that there isn’t real closure. London authorities still haven’t released the official cause of death, and while I’m confident it will someday come, I’d really hoped it would be before the end of the year. My New Year’s Resolution is to never take anything or anyone for granted and to try my best to live in the moment, because it really is all we have. I miss Heklina.

I’m thinking about our friend today. Heklina was obsessed with birthdays and she threw sooooo many of us celebrations over the years. For many years at T-Shack she’d have a cake for us regular performers who had a birthday that particular week. She always got it from that X-rated Cake Gallery on 9th Street and those cakes were DELICIOUS. After T-Shack ended she threw my big 40th bash here in SF and was all too happy to roast me when I turned 45. She had already planned to throw me a big 50th Birthday Bash this weekend as my actual birthday is tomorrow, but it never came to be. I wasn’t inspired to still have a big party, but am content remembering all of the many birthday celebrations so many of us had because of Heklina.
